# Section I: Introduction to LINUX

## 1.1: Logging onto Computers using SSH and SFTP

### 1.1.1. Computers Available

At the University of Lethbridge there are a variety of computers available for computational chemistry. In the Spring 2007 semester, a dedicated computer cluster URACIL (**U**pscale and **R**obust **A**bacus for **C**hemistry **I**n **L**ethbridge) was established, which is composed of 680 cores linked together to work on chemistry problems. This semester you will use this powerful computer cluster to run your assignment calculations. You can access these machines from any Windows machine on campus by logging onto **uracil.resrch.uleth.ca**.

Many computational chemistry problems can be broken down into simpler problems, which can be run over multiple computers. This is called parallel computing. It has a distinct advantage for computational chemistry since the more accurate the level of theory or the more atoms in a molecule, the longer the calculation will take. Allowing multiple computers to work on a problem at the same time means that the calculation will finish faster.

The cluster runs the CentOS Linux operating system and contains 85-compute nodes, which are controlled by one masternode. When you log onto URACIL, you are on the masternode. This computer is the interface between you and the computers running your calculations (the compute nodes). Each compute node contains two quad-core processors, 146 GB of disk space (approximately 122 GB of scratch (temporary) space for running calculations) and 4 GB of memory. Twelve compute nodes contain 8GB of memory (compute-2-0 to compute-2-11), where the compute nodes are numbered according to the rack they are in (0, 1 or 2) and their position in the rack (0 - 29 for racks 0 and 2, or 0 - 24 for rack 1). In summary, URACIL contains 680 cores (i.e., home computers) linked together. This means that URACIL has a peak performance of 5 TFlops or, in other words, URACIL can perform 5 trillion mathematical decisions per second!

### 1.1.2. Usernames & Passwords

**URACIL**

Your username is your University of Lethbridge username listed within the Bridge. Your initial password will be set by the system administrator to be your 9 digit University of Lethbridge student ID number. This **password must be changed immediately** by using SSH to access URACIL (see SSH section below) and type 'passwd', and then hit the 'enter' key and follow the instructions on the screen. Note that your password can be alphanumeric (contain numbers and letters, but no special characters), is case sensitive and cannot spell a word. When you enter your new password the cursor will not move, this is to prevent other people from seeing how many characters your password is.

### 1.1.3. SSH

On any Windows machine on campus, you can access the SSH program you need to access to URACIL to run calculations. From the Windows Start Menu, choose 'All Programs', 'SSH Secure Shell', then 'Secure Shell Client'. A screen will appear (Figure 1) and then just simply click on Quick Connect.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 1. Appearance of the SSH window at start up.

Type the host name (computer you want to log on to, e.g., **uracil.resrch.uleth.ca**) and your username. Click on the Connect button. You will then be prompted to enter your password.

Once logged on, the screen will show your username and the name of the computer you logged onto (URACIL).

### 1.1.4. SFTP

You will need to transfer files between the computers running the calculations (URACIL) and the computer you are using to set up and view these calculations (your computer running Windows). In order to transfer files between computers, you will use SFTP, which is within the SSH program.

On Any Windows Machine on Campus:

Open SSH on your Windows machine, click on Quick Connect, enter the name of the computer you want to logon to (URACIL), your username and password. You can then use the ![](data:image/png;base64,) icon from the SSH folder to transfer files to any drive on your computer.

A new window will appear (Figure 2):

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 2. Appearance of the SFTP transfer window.

The left side of the SFTP window shows files on the Windows machine, and the right side shows files on the Linux computer (URACIL). Files can be transferred by using the mouse to click the desired file and drag the file to the window corresponding to the computer you want the file transferred to.

You must transfer input and output files (.com and .log) in the ASCII text format. In English, this means that the <sub>![](data:image/png;base64,)</sub> icon is chosen from the toolbar. If another button is chosen, errors occur in your calculations. So, always ensure that the <sub>![](data:image/png;base64,)</sub> icon is chosen. However, if you wish to transfer .fchk files to view orbitals, etc, (which you will need to do at various stages in this class) or .pdf files, then the <sub>![](data:image/png;base64,)</sub> icon will not work. Instead, you will need to use the binary format, which means clicking the ![](data:image/png;base64,) icon. To summarize, ![](data:image/png;base64,) is ONLY used for .fchk and .pdf files, and the <sub>![](data:image/png;base64,)</sub> icon is used for everything else.

## .2: Introduction to VI

### 1.2.1. Starting VI

VI is the name of a program we can use to create and edit our files. This program is similar to other text programs, such as Word or Notepad and is extremely powerful.

To start VI, simply type the letters vi followed by the name of the file you wish to create or edit. For this tutorial, type "vi poem.txt" and then press enter. You will see a new screen with a column of tildes along the left side. vi is now in command mode. Anything you type will be understood as a command, not as text to be input. In order to input text, you must type a command. The two basic input commands are the following:

`i` insert text to the left of the cursor

`a` append text to the right of the cursor

Since you are at the beginning of an empty file, it doesn't matter which of these you use. Type one of them, and then type the desired text. For example, you can type some of the following text (a poem by Augustus DeMorgan found in _The Unix Programming Environment_ by B.W. Kernighan and R. Pike):

```
Great fleas have little fleas;
upon their backs to bite 'em;
And little fleas have lesser fleas;
and so ad infinitum.
And the great fleas themselves, in turn,
have greater fleas to go on;
While these again have greater still,
and greater still, and so on.
```
Note that you press the `Esc` key to end insertion and return to command mode.

Using the arrow keys on the key pad will move the cursor. The mouse can be used to highlight and copy text, but it will not move the cursor.

These commands may be repeated by holding the key down. Try moving around in your text now. If you attempt an impossible movement, e.g., pressing the letter k when the cursor is on the top line, the screen will flash, or the terminal will beep. Don't worry, it won't bite, and your file will not be harmed.

### 1.2.2. Deleting Text

`x` delete the character at the cursor

`dd` delete a line

Move the cursor to the second line and position it so that it is underneath the apostrophe in _'em_. Press the letter `x` , and the `'` will disappear. Now press the letter `i` to move into insert mode and type the letters **th**. Press `Esc` when you are finished.

### 1.2.3. File Saving

`:w` save (write to disk) `:q` exit

Make sure you are in command mode by pressing the `Esc` key. Now type :w. This will save your work by writing it to a disk file.

The command for quitting VI is `q` . If you wish to combine saving and quitting, just type :wq. There is also a convenient abbreviation for :wq - ZZ. If much of your programming work will consist of running a program, encountering a problem, calling up the program in the editor to make a small change, and exiting from the editor to run the program again, then ZZ will be a command you use often. Additionally, if you are working with many files (e.g., editing or viewing a series of Gaussian com/log file), there are several useful commands to navigate through multiple files. For example, :n will move to the next file,:wn will write the current file and move to the next file, and :previous will move to the previous file.

If you have hopelessly messed things up and just want to start all over again, you can type :q! (remember to press the `Esc` key first). If you omit the !, VI will not allow you to quit without saving.

Exit your file poem.txt by typing :wq.

## 1.3 Introduction to Linux Commands

> Adapted from <http://www.ee.surrey.ac.uk/Teaching/Unix/> and <http://www.ctssn.com/>
{.is-info}

**Beware: First, Linux is** **CASE SENSITIVE**! Second, there is no way to learn Linux besides trying the commands yourself. Therefore, make sure you are logged into a Linux account and try commands while reading!

### 1.3.1. Listing Files and Directories - ls (list)

When you first login, your current working directory is your home directory. Your home directory has the same name as your user-name, for example, **stacey.wetmore**, and it is where your personal files and subdirectories are saved.

To find out what is in your home directory, type ls, which lists the contents of your current working directory. There will be some files in your home directory from when your account was first created (water.com, and ethylene.com) as well as the poem.txt file that you created in the 'vi' tutorial.

ls does not, in fact, cause all the files in your home directory to be listed, but only those ones whose name does not begin with a dot (.) Files beginning with a dot (.) are known as hidden files and usually contain important program configuration information. They are hidden because you should not change them unless you are very familiar with UNIX! To list all files in your home directory including those whose names begin with a dot, type

`ls -a`

ls is an example of a command which can take options: -a is an example of an option. The options change the behaviour of the command. There are online manual pages that tell you which options a particular command can take, and how each option modifies the behaviour of the command

### 1.3.2. Uracil File Systems

Before discussing in more detail ways to manipulate files and directories, it is useful to discuss the file system in UNIX and Linux. UNIX and Linux file systems are very different from Windows. Unix and Linux are organized in a hierarchy, starting with "slash" or "/". The rest of the directories and subdirectories continue down from the slash.

The "/" directory is the root directory. This is equivalent to C:\\ in the Windows world. All other partitions within UNIX or Linux are a subset of the root partition.

### The most important directory for the average user is the /home/your.username directory. The /home/your.username directory is the location you are when you log on to the computer. This is the only location users can create and store files

### 1.3.3. Making Directories - mkdir

We will now make a subdirectory in your home directory to hold files. To make a subdirectory called unixstuff in your current working directory type

mkdir practice

To see the directory you have just created, type

`ls`

### 1.3.4. Changing to a Different Directory - cd

The command cd &lt;directory&gt; means "change the current working directory to 'directory'". The current working directory may be thought of as the directory you are in, i.e. your current position in the file-system tree.

To change to the directory you have just made, type

`cd practice`

Type ls to see the contents (which should be empty)

### 1.3.5. The Directories . and ..

Still in the **practice** directory, type

`ls -a`

As you can see, in the **practice** directory (and in all other directories), there are two special directories called "." and ".."

In UNIX, "." means the current directory, so typing

`cd .` _(NOTE: there is a space between_ **_cd_** _and the dot)_

means stay where you are (the **practice** directory). This may not seem very useful at first, but using "." as the name of the current directory will save a lot of typing, as we shall see later in the tutorial.

`..` means the parent of the current directory, so typing

`cd ..`

will take you one directory up the hierarchy (i.e., in this case, back to your home directory).

Note: typing cd with no argument always returns you to your home directory. This is very useful if you are lost in the file system.

### 1.3.6. Pathnames - pwd

Pathnames enable you to work out where you are in relation to the whole file-system. For example, to find out the absolute pathname of your home-directory, type cd to get back to your home-directory and then type pwd

The full pathname will look something like this -

`/home/stacey.wetmore`

### 1.3.7. Copying Files - cp

cp file1 file2 is the command which makes a copy of **file1** in the current working directory and calls it **file2**.

### 1.3.8. Moving Files - mv

`mv file1 file2` moves (or renames) **file1** to **file2**

To move a file from one place to another, use the mv command. This has the effect of moving rather than copying the file, so you end up with only one file rather than two. It can also be used to rename a file, by "moving" the file to the same directory, but giving it a different name. Move the file **poem.txt** to your **practice** directory by typing

`mv poem.txt practice/.`

Type cd practice and ls to see if it has worked.

### 1.3.9. Removing Files and Directories - rm, rmdir

To delete (remove) a file, use the rm command. As an example, we are going to create a copy of the poem.txt file then delete it.

Inside your **practice** directory, type

`cp poem.txt tempfile.txt`

`ls` (to check if it has created the file)

`rm tempfile.txt`

`ls` (to check if it has deleted the file)

You can use the rmdir command to remove a directory (make sure it is empty first). Type mkdir backups and then try to remove the backups directory using the rmdir command. It will only delete this backups directory because it is empty. If backups had any files in it, it wouldn't delete this directory. In the future, when running calculations for your project, consider only removing files if you are absolutely certain you will have no use of them in the future. Often failed calculations can be useful for troubleshooting the issues that caused your calculation to fail. Therefore, it is good practice to create a 'failed' directory to store your failed calculations.

### 1.3.10. Wild Cards - The characters \* and ?

The characters **\*** and ? are called wildcards, The \* character will match against one or more character(s) in a file (or directory) name. For example, in your **practice** directory, type

`ls poem\*`

This will list all files in the current directory starting with "poem..."

Try typing

`ls \*txt`

This will list all files in the current directory ending with "...txt"

The character **?** will match exactly one character. So ls ?ouse will match files like **house** and **mouse**, but not **grouse**.

### 1.3.11. Filename Conventions

In UNIX, there is no concept of "file extensions" like in Windows, which means that you can name files after the period with anything you want! However, you should still try to name your files and directories (which are merely a special type of file) properly. In naming files (directories), characters with special meanings such as **/**,**\***,**&**,**%** etc., should be avoided. Also, **never** use spaces within names. The safest way to name a file is to use only alphanumeric characters, that is, letters and numbers, together with **_** (underscore), - (dash), or . (dot). Additionally, job names can only start with a lower or upper case letter (never a number).

File (directory) names conventionally start with a lower-case letter, and may end with a dot followed by a group of letters indicating the contents of the file. For example, all files consisting of a Gaussian input (the major computational chemistry package) may be named with the ending **.com**, for example, **prog1.com**. Then in order to list all files containing Gaussian input in your home directory, you need only type ls \*.com in that directory.

### 1.3.12. Getting Help: On-line Manuals

There are on-line manuals which give information about most commands. The manual pages tell you which options a particular command can take, and how each option modifies the behaviour of the command. Type man to read the manual page for a particular command. For example, to find out more about the ls command, type

`man ls`

## 1.4: Quick Reference for Linux Commands

Table 1. Commonly Used Linux Commands

| Command             | Function                                  |
| ------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| `ls`                | list files and directories                |
| `ls -a`             | list all files and directories            |
| `mkdir`             | make a directory                          |
| `cd _directory_`    | change to named directory                 |
| `cd`                | change to home-directory                  |
| `cd ~`              | change to home-directory                  |
| `cd ..`             | change to parent directory                |
| `pwd`               | display the path of the current directory |
| `cp _file1 file2_`  | copy file1 and call it file2              |
| `mv _file1 file2_`  | move or rename file1 to file2             |
| `rm _file_`         | remove a file                             |
| `rmdir _directory_` | remove a directory                        |
| `*`                 | match any number of characters            |
| `?`                 | match one character                       |
| `man` command       | read the online manual page for a command |
